&quot;Everything Was Forever, Until It Was No More&quot;
Konrad Smolenski, Polish Pavilion
La Biennale di Venezia 2013

&quot;Everything Was Forever, Until It Was No More&quot;
Konrad Smolenski, Polish Pavilion
La Biennale di Venezia 2013

(2011) 
Six black steel vessels, video screens.

Here's how the author describes his work: &quot;Gigantic black steel vessels emerge from the darkness and invade the entire vertical space they occupy. The seas of the world, each enclosed in its own keel dark, are flapping loudly at our feet, while evocative sound of distant waves and undertows mingle and intersect in the diaphanous space of the environment. A great and exciting water concert living in the constant movement and continuously flowing mutation. The old man's wisdom and craftsmanship, are fused with the most advanced technology in a perfect symbiosis between the present and the future. Everything is ready to set sail on these electronic Noah's Arcs that stretch to the sky for us, disbelieving and astonished contemporary digital natives.&quot;

[explored]

XII Mostra internazionale di architettura &quot;People meet in architecture&quot;
Padiglione della Romania

An attractive redheaded girl walks towards the austrian pavilion.
(Who could she be? bah!)

